        <etym xml:lang="ru">Из %iæ%i + %ikær%i, где <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æ-"/> — негативная
                частица, а %ikær%i — усеченная форма слова <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kæron"/>
                ‘конец’, ‘предел’; %iægær%i, следовательно, — ‘беспредельный’, ‘безмерный’; ср.
                редкое в употреблении <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ægæron"/> ‘беспредельный’. Форму
                %ikær%i находим еще в выражении %ikæræj kæronrnæ%i ‘из конца в конец’.<note n="1">
                        PUT NOTE HERE </note>Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                                        ><lang/><w>kara</w><gloss><q>предел</q></gloss></mentioned>,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="ae"
                        ><lang/><w>karana</w><gloss><q>предел</q></gloss></mentioned>. От %iægær%i
                образовано д. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ægærid"/>, %iægirid%i ‘совершенно’,
                ‘вовсе’. Это же слово находим в <ref type="xr" target="#entry_mæstygær"/>
                ‘вспыльчивый’ и, может быть, в <ref type="xr" target="#entry_wagær"/> ‘тем более’ и
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_īwgær"/> ‘коль скоро’ (?). В выражениях брани
                и упрека — %ide ʽgær fækulaj%i, %ide ʽgæryl %i— следует видеть не %iægær%i, а <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_igær"/> ‘печень’. Из осетинского идут <mentioned
                        xml:lang=""><lang/><w/><gloss><q>eggir</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ce"
                        ><lang/><w>uggur</w><gloss><q>самый</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
                        xml:lang="ce"><w/><gloss><q>наиболее</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ce"><w/><gloss><q>слишком</q></gloss></mentioned>, .%n<bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Bailey._Asica._Suppl."
                        /><biblScope>205</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                                /><biblScope>152</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
        <etym xml:lang="en">From %iæ%i + %ikær%i, where <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æ-"/> is a
                negative particle and %ikær%i is the truncated form of the word <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_kæron"/> ‘end’, ‘limit’; %iægær%i, therefore, is ‘endless’,
                ‘limitless’; cf. rarely used <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ægæron"/> ‘limitless’.
                The form %ikær%i cna also be found in the expression %ikæræj kæronrnæ%i ‘from end to
                        end’.<note n="1"> PUT NOTE HERE </note> Cf. <mentioned xml:lang="kho"
                                ><lang/><w>kara</w><gloss><q>limit</q></gloss></mentioned>,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="ae"
                        ><lang/><w>karana</w><gloss><q>limit</q></gloss></mentioned>. %iægær%i
                derives the Digor<ref type="xr" target="#entry_ægærid"/>, %iægirid%i ‘completely’,
                ‘at all’. The same word can be found in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_mæstygær"/>
                ‘irascible’ and, probably, in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_wagær"/> ‘a fortiori’
                and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_īwgær"/> ‘since’ (?). In expressions of abuse and
                reproach %ide ʽgær fækulaj%i, %ide ʽgæryl %i one should see not %iægær%i but <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_igær"/> ‘liver’. The Ossetian origin can be found
                in <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w/><gloss><q>eggir</q></gloss></mentioned>,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="ce"
                        ><lang/><w>uggur</w><gloss><q>most</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
                        xml:lang="ce"><w/><gloss><q>best</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ce"><w/><gloss><q>too</q></gloss></mentioned>, .%n<bibl><ref
                                target="#ref_Bailey._Asica._Suppl."
                        /><biblScope>205</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                                /><biblScope>152</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
